<worksheet >
    <title>FUN-2 Equations of Lines, Planes, and Surfaces</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>To earn an M on this outcome, you will need to correctly complete both problems. To earn a P on this outcome, you will need to correctly complete 
        two parts of each problem.</p>
  </introduction>  
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="1.5in">
        <introduction><p>A plane is defined by the equation <m>5x-y+4z=12</m></p></introduction>
      <task><statement><p>Give an equation of a plane parallel to the given plane and passing through the point <m>(-1,-2,3)</m>.</p></statement></task>
      <task><statement><p>Give a parameterization of the line passing through the point <m>(3,0,4)</m> orthogonal to the given plane.</p></statement></task>
      <task><statement><p>What is the angle between the given plane and the <m>xy</m>-coordinate plane? <em>(Give an exact simplified answer 
        which should contain an inverse trigonometric function.)</em></p></statement></task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
  <page>
    <title>FUN-2 Equations of Lines, Planes, and Surfaces</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>To earn an M on this outcome, you will need to correctly complete both problems. To earn a P on this outcome, you will need to correctly complete 
        two parts of each problem.</p>
  </introduction>  
    <exercise workspace="1.5in">
        <introduction><p>For each surface, sketch the graph, label any intercepts, and give a brief description of the surface.</p></introduction>
      <task><statement><p><m>x^2+y^2-z^2=1</m>.</p></statement></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>z^2-x^2-y^2=1</m>.</p></statement></task>
      <task><statement><p><m>z^2-x=0</m>.</p></statement></task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet>